# Implementation Plan: OAuth 2.1 (Clerk as AS) for the Metrimap MCP resource server

## 1. Research findings — Clerk MCP server-side API (verified)

Sources used:
- Clerk MCP tools repo: https://github.com/clerk/mcp-tools (core `server.ts`, `express/README.md`)
- Clerk Express "Build an MCP server": https://clerk.com/docs/expressjs/guides/ai/mcp/build-mcp-server
- Clerk Next "Build an MCP server": https://clerk.com/docs/nextjs/guides/development/mcp/build-mcp-server
- `authenticateRequest` reference: https://clerk.com/docs/references/backend/authenticate-request
- How Clerk implements OAuth: https://clerk.com/docs/guides/configure/auth-strategies/oauth/how-clerk-implements-oauth

Key API facts (these drive the code design):

**Protected Resource Metadata (RFC 9728).** `@clerk/mcp-tools` exposes framework‑agnostic core helpers from `@clerk/mcp-tools/server`:
- `generateClerkProtectedResourceMetadata({ publishableKey, resourceUrl, properties? })` → returns the RFC 9728 JSON object. It derives Clerk's issuer (FAPI, `https://clerk.canvasm.app`) from the `pk_live_...` publishable key and sets `authorization_servers` to it. `resourceUrl` is our resource id (`https://mcp.canvasm.app/mcp`).
- `generateProtectedResourceMetadata({ authServerUrl, resourceUrl, properties })` — lower-level variant if we want to hardcode the issuer.
- `corsHeaders` — exported constant with the CORS headers MCP clients expect on the metadata endpoint.
- The Express sugar `protectedResourceHandlerClerk({ scopes_supported })` and `authServerMetadataHandlerClerk` are Express-middleware wrappers around the above; since our server is **vanilla `node:http`, not Express**, we use the core `server` helpers and write the response ourselves.

**Token verification.** Use `@clerk/backend`:
```ts
import { createClerkClient } from '@clerk/backend';
const clerk = createClerkClient({ secretKey, publishableKey });
const { isAuthenticated, toAuth } = await clerk.authenticateRequest(request, {
  acceptsToken: 'oauth_token',
  authorizedParties: ['https://claude.ai', 'https://claude.com'], // optional allowlist
});
```
`request` is a Fetch `Request` (Node ≥18 has global `Request`; build it from the node req URL + headers). On success `toAuth()` returns a machine-auth object whose `userId` is the Clerk `user_...` id (exactly what Supabase `requesting_user_id()` expects as JWT `sub`). It also exposes `scopes` and `clientId`. Org info is **not reliably present** on an OAuth machine token (see §4). Alternative: `@clerk/mcp-tools` `verifyClerkToken(auth, token)` maps to MCP SDK `AuthInfo` (`{ token, scopes, clientId, extra:{ userId } }`) — useful if we later want scopes; not required for v1.

**401 challenge.** The middleware `mcpAuthClerk` returns `401` + `WWW-Authenticate: Bearer resource_metadata="<url>/.well-known/oauth-protected-resource"`. We replicate that header manually in vanilla node (one string).

**AS metadata / DCR.** We do **not** need to host `/.well-known/oauth-authorization-server`, `/register`, `/authorize`, or `/token`. Clerk serves its own AS metadata + Dynamic Client Registration + authorize + token endpoints at the FAPI domain `clerk.canvasm.app`. MCP clients read our protected-resource doc, follow `authorization_servers` → Clerk, fetch Clerk's AS metadata, DCR-register, and run the PKCE flow entirely against Clerk. (Optionally we can also serve `authServerMetadataHandlerClerk` for older clients that look for AS metadata on the resource origin, but treat it as optional.)

**Clerk Dashboard actions the owner must do (verified requirements):**
1. Create a **Clerk Secret Key** for the production instance (`sk_live_...`) — none exists server-side today. This is the single most important prerequisite.
2. In the OAuth/AI settings, **enable Dynamic Client Registration** for the production instance.
3. Configure the **OAuth application / scopes** (`profile`, `email`, and any custom scope we advertise) and bind the resource/audience to `https://mcp.canvasm.app/mcp`.
4. Confirm the FAPI domain is `clerk.canvasm.app` (already the case).

## 2. Server routing changes — `mcp-server/server.ts`

Current bug: auth is resolved lazily inside each tool and failures become tool-level `isError`, never HTTP 401 — so Claude never starts the handshake. Fix by resolving auth up front and returning HTTP 401 + `WWW-Authenticate`.

Concrete edits:

a. **Env validation.** Add `CLERK_SECRET_KEY` (required for OAuth) and `CLERK_PUBLISHABLE_KEY` (`pk_live_...`, needed to generate metadata) to the destructure and the missing-env check. Add `MCP_PUBLIC_URL` (default `https://mcp.canvasm.app`) so the resource id and metadata URL aren't hardcoded. Keep the existing `SUPABASE_*` required.

b. **Build a composite resolver** instead of only `createApiKeyAuthResolver`:
```ts
const resolveApiKey = createApiKeyAuthResolver({ ... existing ... });
const verifyOAuthToken = makeClerkVerifier({ secretKey: CLERK_SECRET_KEY, publishableKey: CLERK_PUBLISHABLE_KEY });
const resolveOAuth = createOAuthAuthResolver({
  jwtSecret: SUPABASE_JWT_SECRET, supabaseUrl: SUPABASE_URL, anonKey: SUPABASE_ANON_KEY,
  verifyOAuthToken,
});
const resolveAuth = createCompositeAuthResolver({ apiKey: resolveApiKey, oauth: resolveOAuth });
```
`createCompositeAuthResolver` (new, shared lib): extract the bearer/`x-api-key` token; if it starts with `mk_live_` → `apiKey`; else if present → `oauth`; if absent → throw `McpToolError('unauthenticated', ...)`. (Prefix `mk_live_` is confirmed in `src/shared/lib/supabase/services/apiKeys.ts:29`.)

c. **New metadata routes** (before the POST handler):
```ts
const RESOURCE_URL = `${MCP_PUBLIC_URL}/mcp`;
const PRM_PATH = '/.well-known/oauth-protected-resource';
// GET PRM (and the path-suffixed variant /.well-known/oauth-protected-resource/mcp)
if (req.method === 'GET' && req.url?.startsWith(PRM_PATH)) {
  const meta = generateClerkProtectedResourceMetadata({
    publishableKey: CLERK_PUBLISHABLE_KEY, resourceUrl: RESOURCE_URL,
    properties: { scopes_supported: ['profile', 'email'] },
  });
  res.writeHead(200, { 'content-type': 'application/json', ...corsHeaders });
  res.end(JSON.stringify(meta));
  return;
}
if (req.method === 'OPTIONS' && req.url?.startsWith(PRM_PATH)) { // CORS preflight
  res.writeHead(204, corsHeaders); res.end(); return;
}
```
(Serve at both `/.well-known/oauth-protected-resource` and `/.well-known/oauth-protected-resource/mcp` since clients derive the path from the resource. Optionally add `GET /.well-known/oauth-authorization-server` via `authServerMetadataHandlerClerk` equivalent — optional.)

d. **Gate POST /mcp behind auth** to trigger discovery. Resolve auth once, up front; on failure emit 401:
```ts
const body = await readJson(req);
let authed;
try {
  authed = await resolveAuth({ headers: headersOf(req) });
} catch (e) {
  const isAuthErr = e instanceof McpToolError && e.code === 'unauthenticated';
  if (isAuthErr) {
    res.writeHead(401, {
      'content-type': 'application/json',
      'WWW-Authenticate': `Bearer resource_metadata="${MCP_PUBLIC_URL}${PRM_PATH}", error="invalid_token"`,
      ...corsHeaders,
    });
    res.end(JSON.stringify({ error: 'unauthorized' }));
    return;
  }
  throw e;
}
const server = buildMcpServer(authed);  // pass the resolved ctx in
```

e. **Simplify `buildMcpServer`** to accept the already-resolved `McpAuthContext` (instead of headers + lazy `getCtx`). Tools use `authed` directly; the try/catch inside tools still maps `McpToolError` → `isError` for non-auth errors. This removes the lazy `resolveAuth({headers})` seam from the hot path.

**Tradeoff to note explicitly:** gating all POST /mcp (including `initialize`/`tools/list`) means an unauthenticated client can no longer list tools anonymously. That is exactly what makes Claude's web/desktop connector begin the OAuth handshake (it POSTs `initialize`, receives 401 + `WWW-Authenticate`, then runs discovery/DCR/PKCE against Clerk). CLI/API-key users are unaffected because they already send `Authorization: Bearer mk_live_...` on every request. This is the intended, spec-compliant behavior.

## 3. New resolver — `src/shared/lib/api/mcp/auth/oauthResolver.ts`

Mirror `apiKeyResolver.ts` shape, **inject** the Clerk verifier so the shared lib never statically imports `@clerk/backend` (keeps Clerk's node-only code out of the browser bundle — same DI pattern as `lookupKey`/`supabaseApiKeyLookup`):

```ts
export type OAuthTokenVerifier = (token: string) =>
  Promise<{ userId: string; orgId?: string | null; scopes?: string[] } | null>;

export interface OAuthAuthOptions {
  jwtSecret: string; supabaseUrl: string; anonKey: string;
  verifyOAuthToken: OAuthTokenVerifier;
  tokenTtlSec?: number;
  scopes?: McpScope[];
  scopedClientFactory?: (jwt: string) => SupabaseClient<Database>;
}

export function createOAuthAuthResolver(opts: OAuthAuthOptions): AuthContextResolver {
  const makeScopedClient = opts.scopedClientFactory ?? /* same createClient(...) as apiKeyResolver */;
  return async (req) => {
    const token = extractBearer(req.headers);            // shared helper
    if (!token) throw new McpToolError('unauthenticated', 'Missing OAuth token.');
    const found = await opts.verifyOAuthToken(token);
    if (!found) throw new McpToolError('unauthenticated', 'Invalid or expired OAuth token.');
    const jwt = await mintSupabaseJwt(                     // REUSE the shared seam
      { sub: found.userId, orgId: found.orgId ?? null },
      opts.jwtSecret, opts.tokenTtlSec);
    return { userId: found.userId, client: makeScopedClient(jwt), scopes: opts.scopes ?? ['read','write'] };
  };
}
```

Also add a **composite** to the same auth dir (e.g. `auth/compositeResolver.ts`) exporting `createCompositeAuthResolver({ apiKey, oauth })` plus a shared `extractBearer(headers)` (factor the token extraction out of `apiKeyResolver.extractApiKey`).

**Clerk verifier lives in the node-only mcp-server**, new file `mcp-server/clerkAuth.ts`:
```ts
import { createClerkClient } from '@clerk/backend';
export function makeClerkVerifier({ secretKey, publishableKey, authorizedParties }): OAuthTokenVerifier {
  const clerk = createClerkClient({ secretKey, publishableKey });
  return async (token) => {
    const request = new Request(`${process.env.MCP_PUBLIC_URL}/mcp`, {
      headers: { authorization: `Bearer ${token}` },
    });
    const { isAuthenticated, toAuth } = await clerk.authenticateRequest(request, {
      acceptsToken: 'oauth_token', authorizedParties,
    });
    if (!isAuthenticated) return null;
    const a = toAuth();
    return { userId: a.userId, orgId: a.orgId ?? null, scopes: a.scopes };
  };
}
```

**Exports** — add to `src/shared/lib/api/mcp/index.ts`: `createOAuthAuthResolver`, `type OAuthAuthOptions`, `type OAuthTokenVerifier`, `createCompositeAuthResolver`, `extractBearer`.

## 4. Org/workspace handling — recommendation and tradeoff (main open decision)

The RLS policy (`supabase/migrations/20260629150000_workspace_org_scoping.sql`) is:
`SELECT USING (created_by = requesting_user_id() OR (requesting_org_id() IS NOT NULL AND workspace_id = requesting_org_id()))`.

**v1 recommendation — personal scope (mint `sub`-only JWT, no `o.id`).** Because Clerk OAuth machine tokens don't carry a workspace/org, mint the Supabase JWT with only `sub = clerk user id`. RLS then grants the OAuth user every row where `created_by = <their user id>` — i.e. their personally-created canvases. This works today with zero DB changes and reuses `mintSupabaseJwt` unchanged (pass `orgId: null`).

**Tradeoff (must be surfaced to the owner):** an OAuth-connected user will see/act only on canvases **they created**, not workspace/org-shared canvases authored by teammates (those need `requesting_org_id()` = the workspace id). The API-key path keeps full workspace scope because `mcp_resolve_api_key` returns the key's bound `workspace_id`.

**v2 upgrade path (when needed):** add a `SECURITY DEFINER` RPC mirroring `mcp_resolve_api_key`, e.g. `mcp_resolve_default_workspace(p_user_id text) RETURNS text`, returning the user's default/primary workspace id; have `makeClerkVerifier` (or the resolver) call it and pass `orgId` into `mintSupabaseJwt`. The open question is disambiguation when a user belongs to multiple workspaces — pick a deterministic default (e.g. earliest-created owned workspace) or, better, map Clerk Organizations → workspace and read the org from the token once org-scoped OAuth is enabled in Clerk. Flag this as the deliberate v1→v2 decision.

